## Key concepts

| Concept | Role in the exploit |
|---|---|
| **Format string vulnerability** | `printf(buffer)` lets us read/write stack memory |
| **`%x` / `%N$x`** | Read values from the stack to find our buffer offset |
| **GOT (Global Offset Table)** | Holds function addresses; overwriting `exit@GOT` redirects execution |
| **`%hn`** | Writes a **2-byte** `short` (length modifier **`h`**) — half of a 32-bit pointer per write |
| **`%hhn`** | Optional: writes **1 byte**; padding still comes from **`%Nx`**, not from `h` |
| **NOP sled** | Provides a wide landing zone so we don't need a perfectly exact address |
| **Shellcode** | Machine code that calls `/bin/sh` to give us a shell |
| **Little-endian** | x86 stores bytes in reverse order; addresses must be written accordingly |
| **Environment variable** | A convenient place to store shellcode in the process memory |